Description.caption: Text on negative sleeve: Vernon, W.T. Bishop.|~|Handwritten on negative: Harold W. Vermilyea, Haines Gardner, Fredrick A.
Description.note: From left to right, Inspector H.K. Gardner of the Ontario Provincial Police, murder suspect Harold W. Vermilyea, and Detective Sergeant Frederick Isard of the Belleville Police Department standing in a room with two framed photographs and stencilled borders on the walls, carpeting, curtains, and a chair. Title: J. K. Fronk, ex-parole officer, arrested for bad checks, Los Angeles, 1926
Description.caption: Handwritten on negative sleeve: Fronk, J. H., parole officer|~|Text accompanying photograph in newspaper: His Wizardry Under Scrutiny, J. K. Fronk|~|Handwritten on negative: J. K. Fronk
Description.note: This photograph appears in "Fronk Bankers to Tell Story," Los Angeles Times, 17 Feb 1926: 9.|~|J. K. Fronk, parole officer, was arrested, along with Orison R. Ruddy, bookkeeper, and L. A. Landon, bank manager, for writing bad checks and swindling over $300,000 from 8 banks. He was convicted and sentenced to 10 years, of which he served 4 1/2 years before being paroled in 1931. He then violated his parole and disappeared, and was found dead in Omaha, Nebraska in 1932.|~|J. K. Fronk, parole officer, sits in a wooden chair on a raised wooden platform, posing for a photograph in a three piece suit. He has his feet splayed in front of him, leaning forward slightly, resting his left hand on his knee and his right arm on his thigh. He holds a paper in his right hand. He is staring forwards from his position, unsmiling. A calendar from presumably 1926 hangs on the wall behind him.

Title: Excavation event at the Fort Moore Hill entrance to the Broadway Tunnel, Los Angeles, 1934
Description.caption: Text from negative sleeve: Los Angeles County Buildings
Description.note: View towards the Broadway Tunnel and Fort Moore Hill from the intersection of Spring Street from the intersection with Sunset Blvd. (now Cesar Chavez Avenue). At the base of the hill a group of people gather around Myers & Co. On a platform cordoned off with a stars and stripes fabric the group of men includes Mayor Frank L. Shaw, and another man speaks into a microphone. Signs read "Myers & Co., Excavating Contractors, MU.6306". A billboard advertisement for the movie "Tarzan and his Mate" dates the photograph to 1934. A second billboard reads "No extra cost for Tetraethyl, the higher anti-knock Leader". A sign on a large house on top of the hill, known as the Banning Mansion, reads "Apartments".

Title: Notes written by Aimee Semple McPherson, [1926]

The newspaper report starts "Scribbling as she read from the well-worn Bible given her by graduates of her first Bible class, Aimee Semple McPherson, noted evangelist, believed victim of the sea, left these notes as a last message to her flock before death claimed her."|~|From note: "Light & Darkness...The Radiant Light...Never Bright-No Shade... Light Eternal--The Lamb is the..."|~|In 1926 evangelist Aimee Semple McPherson disappeared from Venice Beach in California  for 5 weeks. Thought to have drowned, she emerged in Mexico, claiming to have been kidnapped. A grand jury investigation indicated that she had actually been staying with a former employee, Kenneth Ormiston. The case against McPherson was finally dismissed.

Description.caption: Text from negative sleeve: MCNAMEE, LUKE ADM.|~|Handwritten on negative: L-R Luke McNamee, Admiral Hyakutake, Conuel Satow, Admiral Leigh
Description.note: Spectators watch as these four men pose for a photograph standing at a banquet table.|~|Rear-Admiral McNamee was a businessman and in the navy. Vice-Admiral Leigh was commander of the battle force and was replaced by Luke McNamee. (Admiral Leigh became commander in chief of the United States fleet). Title: U.S. Chamber of Commerce president John W. O'Leary, his wife Alice O'Leary, and Western Division Chamber of Commerce secretary David A. Skinner, Los Angeles, 1925
Description.caption: Handwritten on negative: R to L, JW O Leary, Mrs JW O Leary, David A Skinner.|~|Text from negative sleeve: O'Leary, John W. & Mrs., Chicago banker, 1929.
Description.note: From right to left, John W. O'Leary, Alice O'Leary, and David A. Skinner standing on a train platform. All are wearing hats, the men are wearing suits, and Mrs. O'Leary is wearing a coat trimmed with fur. In the background, a man is pushing a wheelbarrow. This photograph may have been taken when John W. O'Leary--banker, manufacturer, and president of the United States Chamber of Commerce--arrived in Los Angeles from Oklahoma City on the Southern Pacific with his wife Alice O'Leary and David A. Skinner, secretary of the Western Division Chamber of Commerce, on December 4, 1925. Mr. O'Leary spent the day in Los Angeles, where he met with he Southern Division Chambers of Commerce and was briefed on business conditions in the region.|~|This photograph is similar to another one of John W. O'Leary captioned, "CHAMBER HEAD VISITS IN CITY: John O'Leary of New York on Way to Seattle Sessions National Business Conditions Declared at High Level Huge Advances in Commerce Seen by National Chief," Los Angeles Times, 5 Dec. 1925: A7.

Title: Orpheus Four male quartet, between 1926 and 1931
Description.caption: Handwritten on negative sleeve: Orpheus Four|~|Handwritten on negative: Orpheus Four
Description.note: Verner Campbell appears in the Los Angeles Times as both Verner A. Campbell (more common) and Verner E. Campbell. In 1921, the Los Angeles City Directory lists a Verner E. Campbell as a vocalist. In censuses, Verner A. Campbell is listed as a musician, and a doctor (Verner Campbell was sometimes referred to as Dr. V. A. Campbell in articles).|~|The Orpheus Four was a popular male quartet from the Orpheus Club, and they had a weekly Sunday evening program on KHJ. Members over the years consisted of Samuel B. Glasse, E. P. Emerson, H. Clayton, Verner Campbell, Paul Adams, Paul Breckinridge, Houston Dudley. Sam Glasse and Verner Campbell were the two consistent members through the group's history. Paul Adams was the second longest member. Between about 1922 and about 1931, their members were Samuel B. Glasse (first tenor), Paul Adams (second tenor), Verner Campbell (baritone), and H. M. Dudley (bass). In the early 30s, Dudley was replaced by Breckinridge, and the Orpheus Four became the White King Male Quartet.|~|The members of the Orpheus Four at this time were Samuel B. Glasse, Paul Adams, Verner Campbell, and H. M. Dudley.|~|Houston Dudley is incorrectly noted as H. N. Dudley in the Los Angeles Times multiple times. His correct name is H. M. Dudley.|~|The Orpheus Four male quartet stand around a podium near some microphones, outside in a stadium. They are singing, and two of them hold sheet music. They all wear long coats over their suits. A brimmed hat lies on a small step near the base of the podium. A wooden folding chair is behind them. They are standing under some kind of rig.
Description.fundingNote: Access to this collection is generously supported by Arcadia funds.

Campbell as a vocalist. In censuses, Verner A. Campbell is listed as a musician, and a doctor (Verner Campbell was sometimes referred to as Dr. V. A. Campbell in articles).|~|The Orpheus Four was a popular male quartet from the Orpheus Club, and they had a weekly Sunday evening program on KHJ. Members over the years consisted of Samuel B. Glasse, E. P. Emerson, H. Clayton, Verner Campbell, Paul Adams, Paul Breckinridge, Houston Dudley, and Kenneth Campbell. In the early 30s, the Orpheus Four became the White King Male Quartet.|~|Date on photograph may be incorrect, for in 1926, the men would have been about in their forties. In 1926, their members were Samuel B. Glasse (first tenor), Paul Adams (second tenor), Verner Campbell (baritone), and H. M. Dudley (bass). However, if this picture was taken earlier, like when Orpheus Four was founded, the singers would have been Verner Campbell, Samuel B. Glasse, E. P. Emerson, and H. Clayton.|~|The four singers are dressed in suits. Three of them sit on a grand piano and the fourth stands in front of it.

Title: Veteran fighter pilot Eddie Rickenbacker reading a telegram, 1930s
Description.caption: Text from negative sleeve: Eddie Rickenbacker|~|Handwritten on negative: Eddie Rickenbacker|~|Some of the text on telegram: [illegible] FROM ITS PATRONS CONCERNING ITS SERVICE; WESTERN UNION; SIGNS: DL = Day Letter, NM=Night Message, NL = Night Letter, LC = Deferred Cable, [illegible] Cable Night Letter; Main Office, 608-610 South Spring St., Los Angeles, Calif. Always Open; [message:] [illegible] LOS ANGELES TIMES LOS ANGELES CALIF. [illegible] RICKENBACKER DUE GLENDALE BY AIR FROM KANSAS CITY [illegible] TO HAVE BEEN [illegible]ERED DIRECTION ARMY AIR MAIL [illegible] BUT REFUSED SIMILAR REQUESTS MADE LINDBERGH WILEY [illegible] WOULD SEE RICKENBACKER [illegible] [tagline:]The quickest surest and safest way to send money is by telegraph [illegible]
Description.note: Eddie Rickenbacker was an American fighter ace in World War I, and had 26 aerial victories, making him America's most successful fighter ace in the war. He also drove race cars and designed the Rickenbacker automobile. He was vehemently against air mail transportation switching from commercial pilots to army pilots, saying army pilots did not have enough experience flying and was resulting in unnecessary accidents and deaths.|~|Eddie Rickenbacker sits in an upholstered chair reading a telegram. In the background is a bar table.|~|The telegram, which mentions Glendale and Kansas City, may be related to Rickenbacker's transcontinental TWA flight carrying air mail, the last one for commercial airlines before the army took over transportation of air mail.
Description.fundingNote: Access to this collection is generously supported by Arcadia funds.

Description.note: On December 26, 1933, Leon Grant McBurney died and according to his will, he left $1000 to Joseph Stalin and President Franklin D. Roosevelt, and $1 to each of his children. Roosevelt and Stalin were contacted and asked to relinquish their claims so the children could get the money, which they both did.|~|Related to "Signature of Stalin Filed Here," Los Angeles Times, 06 July 1935: A1.|~|Isabel McCarty, wearing a cardigan over a crewneck sweater, holds up the affidavit signed by Joseph Stalin.|~|Text on document: IN THE SUPERIOR COURT OF THE STATE OF CALIFORNIA IN AND FOR THE COUNTY OF LOS ANGELES. In the Matter of the Estate of LEON GRANT MCBURNEY, Deceased. NO. 140,526 VOLUNTARY ASSIGNMENT. Comes now JOSEPH STALIN, legatee in the purported Last Will and Testament of LEON GRANT MCBURNEY, deceased, and hereby conveys, assigns, transfers and sets over unto ESTHER LILLIAN DENNISON, AUGUSTA McBURNEY JENSEN, ERVAY McBURNEY, MAY McBURNEY ROSS, ELDRED McBURNEY, JEANNETTE McBURNEY DUNBAR and CLOVA MARIA McBURNEY in equal parts, share and share alike, all of my right, title and interest in and to the estate of LEON GRANT McBURNEY, deceased, and more particularly that legacy of One Thousand Dollars ($1,000.00) bequeathed to me under and by the terms of the said purported Last Will and Testament of said LEON GRANT McBURNEY, deceased. This assignment is made voluntarily without any obligation on my part to be performed. DATED: this [handwritten:] 17/IV [typed:] day of [Stalin's signature], 193[handwritten:]5. ([Stalin's signature]) JOSEPH STALIN [typed words in Cyrillic] [Joseph Stalin hand-printed] [typed Cyrillic and handwritten numbers] N. 3568 [unknown signature] [USSR seal] [typed:] Consul of the Union of the Soviet Socialist Republics at [obscured] that the signature of Mr. A.
Description.fundingNote: Access to this collection is generously supported by Arcadia funds.

Title: Vince Barnett and W. R. Wellman at Barnett's retrial for public drunkenness, Los Angeles, 1935
Description.caption: Handwritten on negative sleeve: 1157. 10/18/35 Vince Barnett; W. R. Wellman; Drunk Trial 10/15/35|~|Handwritten on negative: L2R Vince Barnett, W. R. Wellman 10-15-35
Description.note: The time was 7:34 p.m. as Barnett's trial was at night so him having to appear at trial would not put the film crew's and other actors' jobs on hold.|~|Vince Barnett (left) and W. R. Wellman stand in a crowded wood-paneled courtroom. The audience section is full. Barnett is talking to Wellman, and is gesturing with his right hand. Wellman is looking directly into the camera and is resting his left hand on the room divider's gate. A chandelier hangs from the ceiling. A wall clock over the door has the time at 7:34. A policeman stands outside the door.|~|Related to "Barnett Retrial's Hour Dooms Dream of Officer," Los Angeles Times, 11 Oct 1935: A12.|~|On June 21, 1935, Vince and Genevieve Barnett were arrested for public intoxication after allegedly tearing down posters in the R.-K.-O. Theater. The Barnetts said the posters were torn down by overzealous fans looking for autographs from their friend Wallace Ford. Genevieve Barnett was acquitted; Vince Barnett was found guilty, but was granted a retrial in October.
Description.fundingNote: Access to this collection is generously supported by Arcadia funds.

Title: Firemen in the process of rescuing Clarence Ward, Robert Jeanette and Robert Ellis, Arroyo Seco, 1935
Description.caption: Handwritten on [correct] negative sleeve: 1312. Firemen rescuing boys at Arroyo & Ave 54x. 8-2-35 [stamped:] Aug 8 1935|~|Handwritten on negative: 8-2-35
Description.note: 8-year-old Robert Ellis, 11-year-old Robert Jeanette, and 12-year-old Clarence Ward found themselves stuck on an edge in Arroyo Seco above a 130 foot drop above the valley floor. They shouted for help until citizens heard them and contacted the fire department.|~|Related to "Cliff Traps Three Boys," Los Angeles Times, 03 Aug 1935: A1.|~|Firemen and policemen in the process of rescuing three boys, Clarence Ward, Bobby Jeanette and Bobby Ellis, who had gotten trapped in Arroyo Seco. One fireman carries a boy while scaling down the brush-filled canyon. A second boy has already been rescued and waits at the base of the canyon with a fireman and a policeman. Another person is still up on the canyon wall at the top of the rope.|~|Negative 7774 misfiled in envelope for 7775.
Description.fundingNote: Access to this collection is generously supported by Arcadia funds.

Title: Governor Harry W. Nice of Maryland with his wife Edna and seven others, Los Angeles, 1935
Description.caption: Text from negative sleeve: 1412 -- Gov. Harry W. Nice, Governor of Maryland, 9/26/35, [stamped:] Aug 1 1935.|~|Handwritten on negative: Gov. Harry W. Nice, Mrs Nice.
Description.note: On the far right is Governor Harry W. Nice of Maryland, with his wife Edna, who is seated; they appear to be in a hotel room or a formal room. Standing behind Mrs. Nice is an unidentified man in a suit. Surrounding the man are six unidentified folk performers. This photograph was possibly taken when Governor Nice visited Los Angeles during July 1935 to speak at the Hotel Clark to the Los Angeles County Republican Assembly. While in Los Angeles, Governor Nice and his wife stayed at the Biltmore Hotel, visited M.G.M. studios, and were entertained by Mr. and Mrs. Lafayette S. Rounsavelle.
Description.fundingNote: Access to this collection is generously supported by Arcadia funds.

Title: Three men, including Bill Spaulding and James D. Key, read a newspaper, while two other men stand by, Los Angeles, 1935
Description.caption: Handwritten on negative: Key, Spaulding|~|Text on that can be seen on newspaper front page: INVALID EXTRA HOAX|~|Text on ad: BULLOC[KS] BROADWAY & HILL [illegible] Consider Christmas MONOGRAMMED|~|Text from negative sleeve: 4164. Bill Spaulding, Ted Key's father, UCLA Hoax, 12/5/35 [stamped:] Dec 23 1935
Description.note: Five men are pictured, only James D. Key and William H. Spaulding are identified. One man holds a newspaper and is reading the front page while Key and Spaulding also are looking at the story. Key holds a flashlight to help light the newspaper. A Bullock's ad and crossword puzzle can be seen on the other pages. Key has a gun holstered on his hip. Spaulding has a cigarette in his mouth.|~|James D. Key, night watchman in Beverly Hills, was the father of Clois Francis "Shorty" Key, who pretended to be R. F. "Ted" Key (no relation) in order to play football for UCLA. James Key assisted in covering up his son's fraud. Bill Spaulding was the football coach for UCLA. Upon certainty that Clois F. Key was lying about who he was, he was expelled from UCLA.|~|Related to "U.C.L.A. Football Star Exposed as Impostor: Key Grid Hoax Ended as Evidence Proves 'Ted' is 'Shorty' and Definitely Ineligible," Los Angeles Times, 08 Nov 1935: 1.

Title: Sierra Madre City Council seated at table, Sierra Madre, 1935
Description.caption: Text from negative sleeve: 4258. L. to R. John Froelich. William Lees. Preston Schwartz. Phil Dodson. Dan Lewis. Al Myers. 12-12-35. Sierra Madre City Council. [Stamped:] DEC 31 1935.
Description.note: Seated at a table from left to right, an unidentified man, Sierra Madre city business manager Al Myers, Councilman William Lees, Acting Mayor Preston Schwartz, Councilman John Froelich, city attorney Phil Dodson, Dodson's assistant Dan Lewis, and an another unidentified man. On the table are a ledger, documents, and ashtrays. Four paintings and the American flag hang on the wall behind the men. This photograph was possibly taken on December 11, 1935 when the Sierra Madre City Council decided to invite a Los Angeles County survey to help the city of Sierra Madre consolidate government functions that overlapped between the city and the county.|~|Possibly related to the article, "Sweeping City-County 'Merger' Plan in Sierra Madre Launched by Council," Los Angeles Times, 12 Dec 1935: 10.
Description.fundingNote: Access to this collection is generously supported by Arcadia funds.

Title: Grantland Rice, Paul Gallico, J. Westbrook Pegler, Babe Didrikson, and Braven Dyer, playing golf, Brentwood, 1933
Description.caption: Text accompanying photograph in newspaper: Although she has played only a few games of golf, "Babe" Didrikson, the two-gun gal from Texas, was quick to learn the ins and outs of the game. Here are members of the press who played with "Babe" at Brentwood during the Olympics. Left to right, Grantland Rice, Paul Gallico, Westbroow [sic] Pegler, the heroine herself and Braven Dyer of The Times. Miss Didrikson learned all angles of the game so quickly that she not only forgot to count all strokes but even left out one member of the fivesom. Yep, the gal, certainly is speedy.|~|Handwritten on negative sleeve: Grantland Rice <-- sportswriter & Babe Didrikson (Zaharias) athlete 4282 Wide World Rice & The Babe; [circled] Earl; for Braven Dyer|~|Sportswriters and journalists golfing with multi-talented athlete Mildred "Babe" Didrikson (later "Babe" Didrikson Zaharias) Didrikson Zaharias won two gold medals in track and field in the 1932 Olympics before becoming a professional golfer and winning 10 LPGA championships.
Description.note: This photograph appears in "Nothing Slow About the 'Babe' on the Links," Los Angeles Times, 22 Jan 1934: E4.|~|Left to right: Grantland Rice, Paul Gallico, J. Westbrook Pegler, Babe Didrikson, and Braven Dyer. Dyer wrote for the Los Angeles Times. Gallico was a sportswriter as well as a novelist. Rice wears traditional golfing clothes: plus fours, long golf socks, and a golf cap. The other men wear belted slacks. All the men are wearing button down shirts; Pegler's is collarless, and Rice wears a bow tie. Pegler also is wearing a golf cap. Didrikson wears a midi skirt and a t-shirt with the Olympic logo, and a soft brimmed hat. All five people are holding golf clubs at their sides or in front of them; five golf balls lie on the ground around a hole.
Description.fundingNote: Access to this collection is generously supported by Arcadia funds.

Title: Daughters of the British Empire members Mrs. B.W. Templeman, Cora Dow, Anna Poussette, Ethel Capstaff, Agnes Botterell, and Eva Sedding, Los Angeles County, 1936
Description.caption: Text from negative sleeve: State Daughters of the Br[i]tish Empire, Mrs. William Dow, State president of Washington, B. W. Templeman, vice-president, San Francisco, W. C. Poussette, past national president, E. R. Capstaff, State treasurer, J. H. Botterell, new state president, Frederick Sedding, president of Old People's Home, 4726, [stamped:] Apr 12 1936.
Description.note: Daughters of the British Empire members Mrs. B.W. Templeman, Cora Dow, Anna Poussette, Ethel Capstaff, Agnes Botterell, and Eva Sedding standing in an awning-covered patio. In the background is a building with a Spanish tile roof and pillars. This photograph was probably taken during the sixteenth annual state convention of the Daughters of the British Empire, which took place on March 30-April 1, 1936 at the Women's Athletic Club. Attendees also visited the British Old People's Home in Sierra Madre.
Description.fundingNote: Access to this collection is generously supported by Arcadia funds.

Title: Rose Marie Sheran, Eleanor Devin, Virginia Smith, and Kathryn MacKechnie of the Catholic Women's Club Juniors, Los Angeles, 1936
Description.caption: Text from negative sleeve: [handwritten:] 4727 [typed:] Catholic Women's Club Juniors: Rose Marie Sheran, Eleanor Devin, Virginia Smith, Kathryn MacKechnie [stamped:] Apr 12 1936|~|Text on paper in foreground: [illegible]: PLAYED [illegible] THE NAVY|~|Text accompanying the other photograph that appears with the article: Misses Eleanor Devin, president; Rose Sheran, Virginia Smith and Kathryn MacKechnie of Catholic Women's Club Juniors met for luncheon on Olvera Street, where they discussed plans for the regular dinner meeting at the clubhouse this evening. New members will be honored.|~|Text on signs on back wall: We will mail them for you; Photographic greeting cards; Hand tinted & framed pictures $1.00; You may write them here, Fras[her's]
Description.note: A different photo taken on the same occasion appears in "Catholic Juniors Plan Dinner," Los Angeles Times, 15 Apr 1936: A6.|~|Left to right, Rose Marie Sheran, Eleanor Devin, Virginia Smith, Kathryn MacKechnie stand in a store. They are dressed for an outing, with Devin wearing a jacket and Smith and MacKechnie wearing fur-edged coats. All the women wear hats, with Smith also wearing a small veil. They stand in front of a table covered with a striped tablecloth and displaying lots of either polished stone or wood items like buttons, lamps, ashtrays, small bowls and cups, vases, and candlesticks. Behind them is a postcard display featuring photography by Burton Frasher, an animal skin, and hung paintings.|~|Eleanor Devin was the president of the Catholic Women's Club Juniors.
Description.fundingNote: Access to this collection is generously supported by Arcadia funds.

Title: John F. Starnes Jr. and David Searcy being escorted by Detective Lieutenants C. A. Gillan and R. N. Davis, Los Angeles, 1936
Description.caption: Handwritten on negative sleeve: 4824. John F. Starns Jr. John F. Starns Sr. [circled:] Carlotta Starns. missing neg? Liquor Killing "Brandy murder" [stamped:] Apr 15 193[illegible]|~|Text accompanying photograph in newspaper: A bizarre murder by brandy during a liquor store  hold-up was confessed yesterday by these two youths, John Starnes, left, and David Searcy. Behind them are Detective Lieutenants R. N. Davis, left, and C. A. Gillan, who traced them for three months.|~|Handwritten on negative: John F. Starnes Jr. John F. Starns Sr.
Description.note: A different photograph taken during the same day appears in "Strange Killing During Hold-up Admitted," Los Angeles Times, 23 Mar 1936: A2.|~|On December 23, 1935, John Starnes Jr. and David Searcy robbed a liquor store and killed the owner by forcing him to drink a pint of brandy. On March 22, 1936, the two were arrested and confessed to the crime. Searcy was eventually found guilty of second degree murder, kidnapping, and second degree robbery. Starnes Jr. was found not guilty by reason of insanity.|~|Names occasionally spelled John F. Starns and David Searcey.|~|Five men are walking down a hallway. In front, left to right are John F. Starnes Sr., John F. Starnes Jr., and Detective Lieutenant C. A. Gillan. In back are David Searcy and Detective Lieutenant Ralph N. Davis. Starnes Sr. holds something cupped in his hands and is bending forward, looking at it. The detectives and the father are wearing suits and hats. Starnes Jr. wears an unzipped leather jacket, button down shirt, and belted slacks. Searcy wears a sweater vest over a collared shirt.
Description.fundingNote: Access to this collection is generously supported by Arcadia funds.

Title: Elizabeth Trethaway, Paula Hotchkin, Emily Dorette Sullivan, Lucy May Story, Bernice W. Park, and Susan Kays of the Hollywood Opera Reading Club, Los Angeles, 1936
Description.caption: Text from negative sleeve: 5012.[stamp] APR 29 1936. Opera Reading Club. JR.  L to R- Mrs. Edwin Trethway. Miss Paula Hotchkin. Mrs. C. Thiel Sullivan. Miss Lucy May Story. Mrs. Donald K. Park. Mrs. Graydon Kayas. Womens Clubs.
Description.note: Related to "Junior Clubwomen Forecast Placid Year as Season's Work Being Settled," Los Angeles Times, 25 Apr 1936: A7.|~|Six women are pictured, wearing long flowing dresses (one woman in the background is unidentified). Left to right: Mrs. Elizabeth Trethaway, Miss Paula Hotchkin, Mrs. Emily Sullivan, Miss Lucy May Story, Mrs. Bernice W. Park, Mrs. Susan Kays. Trethaway is seated in a chair, Hotchkin is standing, leaning on the sofa, and the four other women are seated in a large sofa. Sullivan, Story, and Park have open books or binders on their laps (Story and Park are sharing one). Trethaway holds a baton, as if conducting the other women. A small round table is in the center of the chair and sofa, with a plant displayed on top of it. A heavy framed painting hangs above the sofa. An endtable can be seen on the right end of the sofa. A lighting fixture is mounted on the wall, and a heavy large lamp can be seen in the back corner.|~|Susan Kays was Bernice Susan Stchula and divorced Graydon C. Kays by 1940. Elizabeth Trethaway also divorced Edwin Trethaway by 1940. Lucy May Story became Lucy May Olson.
Description.fundingNote: Access to this collection is generously supported by Arcadia funds.

Title: Political cartoon about the John Garner's bid for the Democratic presidential nomination, 1932

Description.note: Political cartoon titled "Hearsed!" with an image of John Garner seated behind a window in a horse-drawn hearse. Beside Garner is a caption "Garner's Presidential Boom" and below the hearse "Hearse Support."|~|Edmund Waller 'Ted' Gale joined the Los Angeles Times in 1907 until he left in 1934 in a dispute over editorial policy. From there he went to the Los Angeles Examiner. Gale was also the man who created the iconic "Miss Los Angeles".

Title: Willametta Keck, Lela Coursen Gates, and Elizabeth Anne Fullerton discussing plans for the Children's Horse Show, Pasadena, 1936
Description.caption: Text from negative sleeve: 5103 - [stamp] May 1 1936.  Willametta Keck. Mrs. C Clifford Gates. Elizabeth Ann Fullerton. Society (Planning Childrens horse show).|~|Text appearing with photograph in newspaper: When Miss Willametta Keck, Mrs. C. Clifford Gates and Miss Elizabeth Ann Fullerton met to discuss plans for the Flintridge Riding Club's thirteenth annual Children's Horse Show on May 23, Mrs. Gates outlined ticket distribution for her assistants. Jean Kentle photo.
Description.note: Willametta Keck, Lela Coursen Gates, and Elizabeth Anne Fullerton sit in a garden in wicker chairs. Keck wears a plaid dress and has her hat on her knee. Gates wears a solid dress, gloves and a hat. She holds a pencil in her right hand and notepad. Fullerton has a clutch purse in her lap, and wears a patterened dress with a pussy bow.|~|This photograph appears in "Children's Horse Show Plans Go On," Los Angeles Times, 03 May 1936: D5.|~|Lela Coursen Gates became Mrs. Roy D. Bayly a few months later (Lela Coursen Bayly): see "Roy D. Bayly, Broker, Weds," Los Angeles Times, 20 Nov 1936: A1.

Title: Jeanne Vaillancourt, Marjorie May, and Virginia Chatterton, members of Chi Alpha Epsilon of Pasadena, Pasadena, 1936
Description.caption: Handwritten on negative sleeve: 5104. Jean Vaillaincourt (w/ mask of Greta Garbo); Marjorie May (w/ Jean Harlow mask); Virginia Chatterton (w/ Zasu Pitts mask). Society. Pasadena Chi Alpha Epsilon sisters in benefit (impersonating film stars) [stamped:] May 1 1936|~|Text accompanying photograph in newspaper: Jean Vaillaincourt, with a masque of Greta Garbo; Marjorie May with a masque of Jean Harlow, and Virginia Chatterton, with a Zasu Pitts replica, are Chi Alpha Epsilon sisters who plan a novel benefit bride-tea and fashion show at the Flintridge Country Club next Saturday. Description.note: This photograph appears in "Greek-Letter Girls to be Film Stars," Los Angeles Times, 03 May 1936: D6.|~|Left to right: Jeanne Vaillancourt, Marjorie May, and Virginia Chatterton. The women are outside on a patio. Vaillaincourt is seated in a wicker chair, May is standing in the middle, and Chatterton sits on the arm of another wicker chair. Vaillaincourt and Chatterton are looking at each other while May looks at the camera. All three hold masks of famous actresses: Greta Garbo, Jean Harlow, and Zasu Pitts, respectively.|~|Virginia Chatterton became Virginia R. Abeel in 1939.

Description.caption: Text from negative sleeve: 6410- [stamp] AUG 25, 1936. Thrift Shop- L to R- Mrs. Ben N. Codd. Mrs. Jeffrey Englehart. Mrs. Harry Rubel. Mrs. Morris Sichel (in front).  Womens Club.|~|Text on coat hangers: GOLDEN [obscured], West 10th St., Los Angeles, Calif.|~|Text on side of truck: THR[IF]T [SH]OPS [obscured] AVE. [obscured] 9969|~|Text on boxes on ground: KEENO DOG & CAT FOOD 48 No. 1 CANS FRAGILE HANDLE WITH CARE THE MAY COMPANY KEENO PA[obscured] [COMPANY] SOUTH [obscured] CALIF.; Libby's 100 FAMOUS FOODS Fruits & Vegetables Libby, McNeill Libby, USA JARS|~|Text on box in truck: [BUL]LOCK'S [W]ILSHIRE

Codd was formerly Stella Scharff. They divorced in 1969.|~|Three women (left to right: Stella S. Codd, Carolyn M. Title: Emily von Romberg with James Ross Clark II and Barbara Clark, Southern California, 1936
Description.caption: Text from negative sleeve: 6483. Emelie [sic] von Romberg (Mrs. Max). Mr. & Mrs. J. Ross Clark III [sic]. [Stamped:] Sep 1 1936
Description.note: Seated at a table on a lawn are, from left, Emily von Romberg (later Tremaine) with James Ross Clark II and his wife Barbara Clark (formerly actress Barbara Fritchie). Three men in white jackets beneath umbrellas are visible in the background.
Description.fundingNote: Access to this collection is generously supported by Arcadia funds.|~|James Ross Clark II was a scion of a wealthy industrialist family. His father died in the sinking of the Titanic. Barbara Fritchie, an actress, was married to Clark from 1934 to 1941. Emily Hall Tremaine, a designer and art collector, was married to Baron Maximilian von Romberg until his early death in an airplane crash in 1938; they had an estate in Montecito.

Title: Letter to the Editor of the Los Angeles Times from John Anson Ford, Sep. 9, 1936
Description.caption: Text from negative sleeve: 7004. Oct 28 1936. Mrs Newton Cleveland. T.M. Carlson & copy of letter from John Anson Ford Co. to times. 10/21/31
Description.note: John Anson Ford (1883-1983) was an American journalist, advertising executive and Democratic Party politician. He was a long-serving member of the Los Angeles County Board of Supervisors.|~|A letter from John Anson Ford the the Editor of the Los Angeles Times, offering corrections regarding an article that appeared in the Times on September 9, 1936. Anson had just been elected chairman of the Democratic County Central Committee and writes that the article, in referring to him as an Epic candidate, was incorrect. He states that he was not endorsed by the Epics, and that he has no plans to run for mayor, concluding "there are people who assume public office, or other public position, for the purpose of sincerely rendering service, and without ulterior purposes. I aim to be such a person." The letter is typed on station with the letterhead: John Anson Ford Company/Advertising - Publicity/916 C. C. Chapman Building/Los Angeles/Established 1920
Description.fundingNote: Access to this collection is generously supported by Arcadia funds.

Title: Letter from Jaime Palmer of the Writers Club Hollywood, 1936
Description.caption: Text From Negative Sleeve: 7088  Nov 3, 1936.WPA Records.  Oct 14, 1936
Description.note: Letter written by Jaime Palmer, 6855 Bonita Terrace, Hollywood, CA on October 7, 1936. The recipient is unidentified. She expresses her appreciation for an invitation from Harry Kohr to assume the chairmanship for the women's luncheon committee of The Authors club. Palmer was involved with the Writers Club of Hollywood in the 1930s. Harry Kohr was an exchange editor, telegraph editor and literary editor with the Kansas City Star newspaper. He retired in 1932 and lived in Los Angeles after that, returning to editorial work during WWII.
Description.fundingNote: Access to this collection is generously supported by Arcadia funds.

Title: John Wuest Hunt in an automobile, 1925-1935 (?)
Description.caption: Text from negative sleeve: 8284. [Stamped:] May 14 37. John W. Hunt. (former ad man , Mann Act, charges, former leader of Father Divine movement on So Cal.) City Desk ask we file 2 enclosed negs under John W. Hunt.
Description.note: John Wuest Hunt, a California millionaire and  follower of cult leader Father Divine, as a younger man in an automobile. In 1937 he was convicted of taking a minor across state lines for "immoral purposes" and sentenced to three years.

Title: Friday Morning Club getting ready for their 46th anniversary, Los Angeles, 1937
Description.caption: Text from negative sleeve: 8434 Miss Betty Ferris (with umbrella) Mrs Earl W. Carlson (ribbon under chin small hat Mrs Martha Brisacher Modern dress Friday Morning Club 41st [i.e. 46th] bday 4-15-37 [stamped:] Apr 21 1937|~|Text from newspaper caption: PLANNING FOR FORTY-SIXTH BIRTHDAY FETE Forty-six years ago, when Friday Morning Club was founded, the above surrey was the last word in flashy conveyances. The club keeps abreast of the times, but the 1891 vehicle will play an important part in the birthday celebration on Thursday at the clubhouse. Members playing leading roles will be Mrs. Earl W. Carlson, in old-fashioned costume; Mrs. Martha Brisacher as the modern girl, and Miss Betty Ferris with the umbrella of the gay nineties. The Friday Morning Club treasures many costumes of that period.
Description.note: A different photograph taken on the same occasion appears under the headline, "Money Management Plan Scanned By P.-T.A. Throughout Nation," Los Angeles Times, 18 Apr 1937: D10.|~|Martha Brisacher is not in this photograph. She is in the accompanying photograph, image 14631, the one that appears in the newspaper.|~|Left to right: Betty Ferris, Gwen Carlson, and an unidentified third woman, who may be Lila Mae Sampson, another member of the Friday Morning Club. Ferris and Carlson are in period costume and sitting in a carriage. Sampson is in modern dress and has her left foot on the step of the carriage and right hand braced on the side of the carriage as if ready to get in. Ferris carries a lacy parasol and Sampson has a purse in her left hand and wears a fancy hat and capelet draped over her shoulders.
Description.fundingNote: Access to this collection is generously supported by Arcadia funds.

Title: Clarence Barker of Barker Bros. Family Furniture Store, in court for bigamy charges, Los Angeles, 1939
Description.caption: Handwritten on negative: Clarence Barker|~|Text from negative sleeve: 15488- [stamp] JAN 31 1939. Clarence Barker (of Barker Bros Family Furniture Store). Breach of Promise. 1-20-39. [Credit Stamp] L.A. Times Photo By Gordon Wallace.
Description.note: Clarence Barker stands in a courtroom with his left hand in his jacket pocket and his right hand holding his hat and some file envelopes. His overcoat is thrown over his right arm. He is in 3/4 profile, facing the left side of the picture. A clock is on the wall behind him between two windows; it reads noon. A metal studded wooden and leather chair is behind him. In the background, a balding man in an overcoat sits on a courtroom bench, holding his hat in his right hand.|~|On November 7, Clarence Barker of Barker Bros. Family Furniture Store, was charged with bigamy for marrying Anna McDonald while still married to Martha Barker. He was also charged for writing bad checks.|~|Related to "Judge Fixes Bigamy Trial: Salesman to Face Double Complaint," Los Angeles Times, 08 Nov 1938: A2.

Description.caption: Text on street signs on light posts: NEW HAMPSHIRE; WILSHIRE|~|Handwritten on negative: 5QO[?]|~|Text accompanying photographs in newspaper: LEADERS VISIT LATEST ADDITION TO CITY'S MERCANTILE ESTABLISHMENTS; Front view of new I. Magnin store, Wilshire Blvd. and New Hampshire Ave.|~|Text on sign by fire hydrant: KEEP TO RIGHT|~|Text from negative sleeve: 15720. (I. Magnin + Co Bldg)|~|Text on sign on far left of photograph: ROBERTS BROS SANDWICHES; Turkey Sandwich 35|~|Text on building sign to right of sandwich shop: WILMO[N]T GARAG[E]
Description.note: Text on main building over main door: I. MAGNIN & CO.|~|A slightly different version of this photograph taken on the same occasion appears in "Store Holds Gay Premiere: Magnin's New Style Center on Wilshire Viewed by Leaders," Los Angeles Times, 11 Feb 1939: 7.|~|The I. Magnin & Co. building at the intersection of New Hampshire and Wilshire in Los Angeles. A five story cube-shaped building. A carving of a stag and two does is at the top of the column over the main doors. To the left, a sandwich shop and a mechanic's garage can be seen. Several cars can be seen parked in front of the building on Wilshire, as well as several cars driving by on Wilshire. Several pedestrians appear in the right side of the photograph.
Description.fundingNote: Access to this collection is generously supported by Arcadia funds.
